  "text": "n the United States we have experienced a relentless rise in the cesarean delivery rate from 5% in the 1960s to 32% today. [CITATION_1] It is unclear what an acceptable rate should be. Certainly the 5% level was too low, and the 32% rate of today is judged by many to be too high. However, recent data show that almost a third of primary cesarean deliveries are in nulliparous women, [CITATION_2] and with the decreasing rate of vaginal birth after cesarean delivery (VBAC) since 1996, the rate is likely to exceed 50% very soon in the United States. How can we curtail this runaway increase in cesarean deliveries? The question is simple, but the solution is complex.",
